Raw Text:
132nd MAINE LEGISLATURE
FIRST REGULAR SESSION-2025
Legislative Document No. 802
H.P. 509 House of Representatives, March 4, 2025
Resolve, Directing the Department of Health and Human Services to
Design a Mentoring Program for Youth Who Have Extended Care
and Support Agreements with the Department
Received by the Clerk of the House on February 27, 2025. Referred to the Committee on
Health and Human Services pursuant to Joint Rule 308.2 and ordered printed pursuant to Joint
Rule 401.
ROBERT B. HUNT
Clerk
Presented by Representative SACHS of Freeport.
Cosponsored by President DAUGHTRY of Cumberland and
Representatives: BRENNAN of Portland, COPELAND of Saco, GRAHAM of North
Yarmouth, ROEDER of Bangor, STOVER of Boothbay, WEBB of Durham, ZAGER of
Portland, Senator: DUSON of Cumberland.
Printed on recycled paper

1 Sec. 1. Department of Health and Human Services contract for mentoring
2 program. Resolved: That the Department of Health and Human Services shall contract
3 with an independent service provider with expertise in foster care and extended care and
4 support agreements to design a mentoring program for youth who have extended care and
5 support agreements with the department pursuant to the Maine Revised Statutes, Title 22,
6 section 4037-A. The contracted independent service provider shall research mentoring
7 programs that are evidence-based to recommend a mentoring program model to the
8 department. The mentoring program must include training requirements for supporting
9 youth transitioning out of extended care and support agreements for mentors, staff and
10 youth, as well as multiple data collection points and data analysis. The contracted
11 independent service provider shall consult with youth who currently have extended care
12 and support agreements or have had extended care and support agreements in the past. The
13 contract must allow for compensation, including supplies and travel, for youth who are
14 involved in the development of the mentoring program. The department shall submit a
15 report to the joint standing committee of the Legislature having jurisdiction over health and
16 human services matters, no later than January 2, 2027, with recommendations for a
17 mentoring program. The report must include the recommendations from the contracted
18 independent service provider, descriptions of youth viewpoints and the department's
19 response to the recommendations. The joint standing committee of the Legislature having
20 jurisdiction over health and human services matters is authorized to report out legislation
21 related to the report to the 133rd Legislature in 2027.
22 SUMMARY
2233 This resolve requires the Department of Health and Human Services to contract with
2244 an independent service provider to design a mentoring program for youth who have
2255 extended care and support agreements with the department. The contract includes
2266 researching mentoring programs that are evidence-based, training requirements for
2277 participants and data collection and analysis. The input of youth who have or have had
2288 extended care and support agreements must be specifically included. The department must
2299 submit a report to the joint standing committee of the Legislature having jurisdiction over
3300 health and human services matters, no later than January 2, 2027, with recommendations
3311 for a mentoring program. The committee is authorized to report out legislation to the 133rd
3322 Legislature in 2027.
